header.gameNote: SEC TOURNAMENT AT NORTH LITTLE ROCK AR

article.headline: Augustus leads LSU to SEC final
article.linkText: Augustus' 29 points leads LSU to easy win over 'Cats
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A fast start by No. 3 LSU proved
to be too much for Kentucky to overcome.

Seimone Augustus scored 12 of her 29 points as the Lady Tigers
jumped out to a 21-4 lead and cruised to a 79-52 victory on
Saturday night.

LSU (27-2) advanced to the championship game of the Southeastern
Conference tournament against No. 8 Tennessee, which beat No. 12
Georgia 89-79 later in the night.

Augustus was one shy of the LSU record she tied the night before
for most points in an SEC tournament game. She shares the record
with LSU coach Pokey Chatman, but Chatman wasn't thinking about
records. She said she is thinking of the games ahead.

"I will never, ever try to stick a player back in there to get
a record," Chatman said. "There's a bigger picture out there."

In Friday's and Saturday's games, Chatman pulled Augustus with
about 10 minutes left.

"Seimone Augustus proved why she was (SEC preseason) player of
the year," Kentucky coach Mickie DeMoss said. "She hit some
unbelievable shots."

Chatman said she wanted to see a strong defense early, and her
team responded.

"It was something that I challenged them with leaving the
locker room," Chatman said.

Augustus contributed with six defensive rebounds. Point guard
Erica White knifed through the Kentucky defense, picking up nine
assists as she fed Augustus.

"I always think Seimone is in the zone," White said. "I never
think she's off."

Chatman said 6-foot-5 center Sylvia Fowles, who limped off the
court with 15:24 to play, injured an ankle but is expected to play
in the championship. Fowles had 11 points on 5-for-8 shooting, and
10 rebounds. She averages 16.9 points per game and 11.6 rebounds.
Scholanda Hoston added 10 for the Lady Tigers.

Nastassia Alcius led Kentucky with 14 points and Sarah Elliott
scored 10.

Alcius ended the early LSU run with a 3 and the Wildcats chipped
away, closing the deficit to 31-21 when Jennifer Humphrey bounced
in a 3 with 3:28 to go in the half.

Chatman called a time out and Kentucky didn't score again in the
half. In the remaining minutes, in addition to forcing turnovers,
LSU quickened its pace on offense, with White showing her speed in
moving the ball up court and getting the ball in for points.

LSU closed the half scoring the last six points to take a 37-21
lead.

In their regular season meeting on Dec. 18, LSU clobbered the
Wildcats 66-36. Chatman said both teams have improved since then.

"We're both better teams. It's a matter of who is out to
execute ... stay true to your strengths," she said.

LSU, which won the SEC regular season title, has made it to the
championship game of the tournament four of the last five years,
but the only time the Lady Tigers won it was in 2003, the last time
the event was in North Little Rock.
